Java handles runtime errors using exception handling with try, catch, finally, throw, and throws.

A try block contains code that may throw an exception, while the catch block handles the exception. The finally block is used for cleanup operations.

Example:

try {
    int result = 10 / 0;
} catch (ArithmeticException e) {
    System.out.println("Cannot divide by zero.");
} finally {
    System.out.println("Execution completed.");
}

This prevents the application from crashing and allows graceful error handling.

I would build a REST API using Spring Boot with endpoints like:

GET /users
GET /users/{id}
POST /users
PUT /users/{id}
DELETE /users/{id}

The application would use a User entity, JpaRepository, Service layer, and REST Controller.

For authentication and authorization, I would use Spring Security with JWT authentication. Users log in with their username and password, which are verified against the database. After successful login, the server generates a JWT token. The client sends this token in the Authorization header for every protected request.

Passwords should be encrypted using BCrypt, HTTPS should be enabled, and role-based authorization (such as ADMIN and USER roles) should be implemented to restrict access to sensitive endpoints.
